Topological Dynamical Membrane Universe (TDMU) Model 2.32
——A Complete First-Principles Formulation Integrating Recursive Weaving, Nuclear Transition Channels, Astrophysical Evolution Criteria, and a Formal Completeness Addendum

Meta-narrative: The Legacy of the Toad

At the bottom of a summer night pond, a toad rests quietly in the water, blowing bubbles. The bubbles rise, expand, deform, oscillate, and ultimately burst, returning to ripples.

In this image:
Water is the substrate—the invisible, all-bearing foundation.
The bubble wall is the cosmic membrane—an ordered structure emerging from the substrate.
The rising of the bubble is time—an irreversible unfolding.
The expansion of the bubble is the cooling and evolution of the universe.
The textures on the bubble are matter—woven structures on the membrane.
The bursting of the bubble is the finale—structural dissolution, return to the substrate.
This is not a metaphor. It is the entire model projected onto another level. Everything we do is merely translating every link in this image into precise combinatorial language.

The toad still rests quietly in the unreachable depths of the substrate. We were born from ripples on the membrane and can never look back upon it in our lifetime—but this does not prevent us from reconstructing its form step by step through the topological imprints on the membrane.

Part I: Ontology

Postulate 1: Substrate

There exists a discrete, background-free combinatorial network ℳ. It consists of nodes and directed edges connecting nodes.

This network is not embedded in any space. It does not evolve within any pre-existing time. The only primitive relationship between nodes and edges is "connected" or "not connected." The sole primitive attribute of an edge is its direction—pointing from one node to another.

The sole dynamics of the substrate is local reconnection: when two edges meet at a node, they can disconnect and reconnect according to directional rules. Reconnection is local—it involves only a few edges sharing the same node, and does not involve distant structures.

Directional Rule: In any reconnection operation, when traversing along any closed path, the difference between the number of counterclockwise edges and clockwise edges remains unchanged.

The substrate contains no physical quantities. No mass, no energy, no charge, no fields. Only nodes, directed edges, and the connection relationships among them.

Definition 1.1: Loop

A closed path starting from a node, traveling along directed edges, and eventually returning to the starting node is called a loop. Loops are the only structures in the substrate with "global recognizability."

Definition 1.2: Topological Charge

On any closed loop, the net algebraic sum of directions traveled along the loop (counterclockwise count minus clockwise count) is an integer. This integer is conserved under reconnection operations—because the directional rule guarantees it.

This integer is called the topological charge of the loop.

Topological charge is not a presupposed physical quantity. It is the name given to the purely geometric fact of "the algebraic sum of directions on a closed path." It does not need to be implanted—it exists naturally in any loop that satisfies the directional rule. Topological charge is a discovery, not an invention.

Postulate 2: Spontaneous Emergence of the Membrane

When, in a certain closure region of the substrate, the loop density (number of closed paths per unit number of nodes) exceeds a critical value, the loops in that region, through collective reconnection, tend to weave into a closed surface. This surface divides the region into an "interior" and an "exterior"—with a different internal loop density than the exterior, and the surface itself becomes the boundary between the two regions.

This closed surface is called the membrane.

The membrane is not "placed into" the substrate. It is a structural pattern that the substrate naturally tends toward under specific loop density conditions. The membrane is a state of the substrate, not something external to it.

Honest Note: The specific numerical value of the critical density cannot currently be derived analytically from the pure combinatorial rules. The model qualitatively describes it as "exceeding a value where the loop connectivity of the closure region is sufficient to support the existence of a closed surface." The determination of this value awaits future numerical simulations or analytical proofs of combinatorial dynamics.

Postulate 3: Weaving Hierarchy

Material structures are composed of topological knots (non-self-detaching weaving subgraphs) arranged in a recursive hierarchy. Interactions between topological knots are realized through shared links. Every item on this recursive growth tree is a topological knot of a specific order, with its total number of proto-bricks determined by the proto-brick counts of its parent knots.

Corollary 3.1: Hierarchical Cutoff Criterion

The shared-link network between topological knots is only counted as an effective interaction when the inter-knot distance is less than or equal to a finite integer multiple of the smaller knot's recursive growth radius.

Specifically, let topological knot A have a recursive order determined by its proto-brick count N_A (with N_A = 4^m in some packing configuration), and let its intrinsic combinatorial radius be r_A = ⌈N_A^(1/3)⌉ (in node steps).

When the center-to-center distance d_AB > κ · (r_A + r_B) (where κ is a shielding factor determined by the local loop density, κ ∈ [1,3]), the total number of shared links N_links decays exponentially below a threshold N_thresh, and can be considered zero in macroscopic physics.

Origin of this cutoff: Intermediate loop density in the substrate cannot sustain stable weaving channels beyond distances exceeding r_A + r_B—any additional links will spontaneously dissolve through reconnection because the intermediate nodes lack sufficient topological charge support.

Physical consequences:

At the nuclear scale (r ~ 1 fm): Cutoff radius far exceeds nucleon spacing; the total number of shared links is geometrically forced to lock at maximum saturation—macroscopically manifesting as the short-range saturation of the strong nuclear force.
At the atomic scale (r ~ 1 Å): Cutoff radius precisely matches the range of the electron cloud; the total shared links naturally decrease with distance according to the number of combinatorial paths—macroscopically manifesting as the 1/r form of the Coulomb potential.
At the cosmic scale (r ≳ 1 Mpc): Cutoff radius matches the highest order of the recursive growth tree (galaxy cluster scale)—beyond this scale, the shared link count falls to zero, macroscopically manifesting as gravitational shielding and the decoupling of cosmic expansion.
Part II: Emergence of Spacetime

Postulate 4: Combinatorial Distance

The distance between two nodes is defined by the number of edges on the shortest path connecting them. The distance between two structures is defined by the number of edges on the shortest path connecting the regions to which they belong.

Distance is not a pre-existing metric in space. It is a direct readout of the connection relationships between nodes.

Postulate 5: Space

The sum total of distance relationships among all structures on the membrane constitutes the spatial structure of the membrane.

Space is not a container that holds the membrane. It is the set of relationships among structures on the membrane.

When a structure moves, it is not traveling through space—it is changing its connection relationships with all other structures. "Motion" is a record of reconnection history on distance relationships.

Postulate 6: Time

The sequential order between two events A and B on the membrane is determined by the cumulative number of reconnection events on the paths connecting them. If the total number of reconnections on any path from A to B is N, and N > 0, then A precedes B; if N = 0, then A and B are simultaneous.

Time is not a dimension, not a coordinate, not a parameter. It is the cumulative count of reconnection events.

Honest Note on the Arrow of Time:

The reconnection process logically permits reverse operations. However, reverse operation requires the system to retain complete information about the connection state prior to reconnection. In a combinatorial network, the recoverability of this information decays exponentially with the length of reconnection history. Therefore, the arrow of time is a statistical fact, not a logical necessity.

The model assumes that our specific membrane region is in an "almost irreversible" reconnection state. The rigorous foundation for this assumption awaits proof.

Part III: Emergence of Material Structure—Recursive Weaving and Energy-Scale Relativity

Postulate 7: Topological Knot

A woven subgraph composed of loops on the membrane that does not automatically disassemble under reconnection dynamics is called a topological knot.

A subgraph does not automatically disassemble if and only if: the number of successive reconnections required to separate it from the rest of the membrane exceeds a threshold. This threshold ensures that no local reconnection operation can release internal stress without destroying the overall structure.

Matter is not pre-existing particles. It is topological knots on the membrane that have reached stability conditions.

Definition 7.1: Stability Parameters of a Topological Knot

The stability of a topological knot is determined by two factors:

Total Internal Links: The number of independent connection paths between loops within the knot. The larger the total, the more reconnection steps required for disassembly.
Boundary Connectivity: The number of connection paths between the surface of the knot and the exterior. The lower the boundary connectivity, the harder it is for external reconnections to invade the interior.
Definition 7.2: Topological Defects and Imperfect Surface Weaving

The surface weaving of any topological knot can never achieve absolute perfect closure—there always exist some regions that cannot be fully covered by existing weaves, called topological defects. The size and distribution of defects depend on the weaving complexity of the knot: knots with fewer proto-bricks have loose weaving, with a larger defect area ratio; knots with more proto-bricks have dense weaving, with a smaller defect area ratio.

Topological defects are the "active sites" for interactions between topological knots. Whether two topological knots can undergo defect-complementary weaving depends entirely on the geometric compatibility of their surface defects.

Definition 7.3: Proto-brick

The smallest topological knot on the membrane that can exist independently and establish stable shared links with other topological knots is called a proto-brick.

The proto-brick is the effective fundamental unit at the current energy scale. Its "elementary nature" is energy-scale-dependent—should future, higher energy scales reveal that proto-bricks are composed of smaller structures, the model can naturally be extended.

Definition 7.4: Mass of a Proto-brick

The ability of a proto-brick to resist directional reconnection—i.e., the number of reconnection events required to change its net loop directional algebraic sum—is defined as the mass of the proto-brick. Mass is the dynamical manifestation of topological charge.

Postulate 8: Recursive Growth and the Spectrum of Topological Knots

Topological knots do not exist in isolation. Under appropriate energy-scale and collision conditions, smaller stable topological knots can combine into larger stable topological knots through the defect-complementary weaving mechanism. Because weaving imperfection is universal, the surface of any topological knot possesses defect regions available for matching. When the defects of two smaller knots are exactly geometrically complementary, they interlock to form a larger woven structure—a process entirely determined by the geometric properties of the defects on both sides, without the need to introduce additional assumptions such as "chirality."

This combination is not arbitrary. Smaller knots that can stably combine into a larger knot must have defect distributions that satisfy specific topological compatibility conditions: the defect distribution of the new knot must naturally be inherited from the defect distributions of the two precursor knots through reconnection, and the merged weaving network must reach a new stability threshold. This compatibility condition does not impose a unique numerical sequence constraint on the proto-brick counts of the precursors, but it tends to select combinations whose defect distributions can "seamlessly splice." From this naturally arises a recursive growth tree of topological knots—starting from the proto-brick, combining generation by generation, forming stable knots of increasing structural complexity and mass. Every item on the recursive tree is a topological knot of a specific order, its total proto-brick count determined by the proto-brick counts of its parent knots.

The existence of a recursive growth tree is a necessary consequence of the defect-complementary weaving mechanism. The topology of the tree—which knots can combine to form which larger knots—is determined by the compatibility of defect distributions. The growth direction of the tree statistically points toward greater proto-brick counts and higher weaving complexity; this is the preferential path of reconnection operations under satisfaction of stability conditions. Whether recursive growth follows a specific numerical sequence (such as a Fibonacci-like sequence) is not currently treated as a necessary requirement of first principles, but is reserved as a question to be derived from, or refuted by, the statistical mechanics of vortex networks.

Definition 8.1: Electron-brick

On the recursive growth tree, a stable topological knot formed by 4 proto-bricks in a specific weaving configuration is called an electron-brick. It is the smallest independent stable knot at the current cosmic energy scale, and is the fundamental building block for all more complex material structures.

The internal structure of the electron-brick also follows the recursive weaving principle: it possesses a rigid core densely woven from those 4 proto-bricks, and possibly a soft outer layer composed of deeper proto-bricks (i.e., knots from earlier generations on the recursive tree) attached to the core through defects. At the current low energy scale of the universe, the mass contribution of this outer layer is extremely tiny and negligible; thus the electron-brick appears observationally as a "point-like" particle of fixed mass.

However, according to the principle of energy-scale relativity, at higher energy scales (such as the very early universe), the outer layer of the electron-brick will gradually be excited, revealing its internal structure. What is called an "elementary particle" is merely an instantaneous snapshot at a given energy-scale step in cosmic history—there are no eternal "fundamentals," only eternal recursion and emergence. If future technology can probe the pre-electron-brick level of structure, the recursive growth law will still apply, and we will be able to reveal deeper layers of material composition. This emergent structure guarantees the theory's potential for infinite extension while consistently maintaining the unity of mathematical form.

Definition 8.2: Exchange Reconnection Number and the Geometric Enforcement of Pauli Exclusion

Definition 8.2a (Exchange Reconnection Number S): Let p_A, p_B be two dangling link ports on the surfaces of two identical topological knots (electron-bricks). The minimum number of local reconnection operations required to move p_A to the original position of p_B and p_B to the original position of p_A is called the exchange reconnection number S.

Lemma 8.1 (Parity of Exchange): For two identical topological knots occupying the same order of the recursive growth tree, the exchange reconnection number S of their ports must be odd.

Proof sketch: The exchange operation of two identical topological knots must be accomplished through braiding exchange (looping along closed paths, rather than directly dragging nodes through each other). Each local reconnection step changes the target node of a directed edge. For a complete braiding exchange of two identical objects, the sequence length k of the braid group B_N exchange generators must satisfy k ≡ 1 (mod 2). The simplest constructive example requires 3 local reconnections. Therefore, S must be odd.

Theorem 8.1 (Geometric Enforcement of Pauli Exclusion): Two identical electron-bricks cannot occupy completely identical geometric positions and phase states.

Proof: If two identical electron-bricks occupy completely identical geometric states, the exchange operation degenerates into the identity operation (0 reconnection steps, even). But Lemma 8.1 requires the exchange reconnection number to be odd. The contradiction odd = even forces the assumption to be false. Two identical electron-bricks must maintain a difference in at least one geometric degree of freedom—either a phase difference Δθ ≥ 1, or occupy distinct spatial winding modes.

Note 8.1 (Shell Filling Numbers): Pauli exclusion forces each electron-brick to occupy mutually distinct geometric states. The discrete winding modes of dangling link ports in three-dimensional space constitute a set of orthogonal basis vectors, the total number of which is determined by the topological degrees of freedom of the network at a given energy scale. For principal quantum number n, the number of available orthogonal winding modes is 2n². This is the geometric origin of the atomic orbital filling numbers 2, 8, 18, 32. The complete derivation of this correspondence—from the discrete combinatorial rules of port winding to a discretized version of spherical harmonics—will be presented independently as a future supplement to TDMU.

Definition 8.3: Baryon-brick (Proton and Neutron)

At orders on the recursive growth tree far higher than the electron-brick, there exist giant stable topological knots formed from numerous electron-bricks and deeper proto-bricks according to recursive rules.

The structure of such topological knots exhibits a universal binary layered pattern:

Rigid Core: Composed of a large number of electron-bricks or equivalent proto-bricks in the closest packing arrangement. For topological knots reaching macroscopic scales, cubic close packing is the optimal arrangement; in this limit, the core proto-brick number asymptotically approaches an integer multiple of 1728 (i.e., 12³). The core provides high binding energy to resist disintegration and serves as the skeleton of the entire structure.
Soft Outer Layer: Composed of a large number of proto-bricks or small topological knots floating on the surface of the core, attached via defect complementarity, forming a deformable buffer layer. Outer layer proto-bricks can slide under external forces, absorbing collision energy, thus protecting the core from penetration during high-energy collision filtering in the early universe. The defect distribution of the outer layer proto-bricks determines the macroscopic charge manifestation of the topological knot—positive, negative, or neutral—depending on the net directional algebraic sum of the outer layer defects.
These two stable configurations observationally correspond to the proton (positively charged) and neutron (electrically neutral). Both share the same "rigid core + soft outer layer" structural pattern, differing only in the net topological charge property of the outer layer defects.

This "rigid interior, soft exterior" binary structure is a universal design of recursive weaving, applicable to all levels from electron-bricks to baryon-bricks and even higher-order atomic nuclei. The only difference between levels is which "interior" and "exterior" are observable at the current energy scale: the outer layer of the electron-brick contributes negligible mass at the current energy scale, the outer layer of the baryon-brick contributes significantly, and the larger scale of atomic nuclei reveals defect networks among nucleons.

Definition 8.4: Total Compressive Binding Energy (E_comp)

A topological knot, as a closed weaving network, possesses a structural threshold for resisting external compression. This threshold is jointly determined by the strength of all binding edges inside the knot, the weaving configuration, and the defect distribution; it is called the total compressive binding energy, denoted E_comp.

E_comp is a single unified physical quantity representing the topological knot's resistance to compression, without presupposing its internal microscopic decomposition structure. Its essence is the structural resistance of the topological knot as a closed weaving network to maintain its configuration. This resistance exists in all topological knots, regardless of whether they are charged. Electrostatic repulsion is merely an apparent form in the charged case, not the essence.

Definition 8.4a (Hierarchical Compressive Tensor): The compressive binding energy E_comp of an atomic nucleus decomposes into three geometrically independent contribution terms:
E_comp = V_core · S_core + V_shell · S_shell + I(suture)
where:
V_core: number of close-packed proto-brick units in the core, determining the main mass number of the nucleus.
S_core: average link saturation of the core. For perfect close packing (such as a 12³ hypercubic closure), S_core → 1.
V_shell: effective number of proto-brick units in the outer shell participating in chemical bonding.
S_shell: outer shell port saturation, determining chemical valence and reactivity.
I(suture): topological stress concentration factor on the core-shell transition suture line, determined by the deviation of suture layer proto-brick arrangement from the ideal closure configuration.

Theorem 8.2 (Chemistry-Nuclear Decoupling Theorem): The spatial orientation of outer shell dangling ports (i.e., chemical valence) depends only on S_shell and the arrangement of outer shell ports, and is independent of the core proto-brick count V_core. In contrast, the suture stress concentration factor I is highly sensitive to discrete changes in the core proto-brick count.

Corollary 8.1 (Vacancy Stress Concentration): If vacancies exist in the core proto-brick arrangement (i.e., the actual proto-brick count is less than the ideal closure count for that weaving tree order), then the topological stress concentration factor at the suture line I > 0. If no vacancies exist, I ≈ 0.

Corollary 8.2 (Difference in Fission Thresholds of Uranium Isotopes):
²³⁸U: core proto-brick arrangement matches the complete closure of a 12³ hypercube, I₂₃₈ ≈ 0, fission trigger threshold high.
²³⁵U: core lacks 3 proto-brick units, vacancies cause I₂₃₅ > 0, fission trigger threshold significantly lower than ²³⁸U.
The chemical properties (S_shell) of the two are completely identical—the outer shell port arrangement is unaffected by core vacancies.

Honest Note: The precise value of I depends on the specific positions of vacancies within the closure, the number of vacancies, and the geometric configuration of the suture. Its complete calculation requires a systematic analysis of stress distribution in 12³ hypercubes under various vacancy configurations. What is provided here is a qualitatively rigorous criterion (I > 0 if and only if vacancies exist), not specific numerical values. The "significant difference" in fission thresholds is a necessary consequence of I being non-zero, independent of the specific magnitude of I.

E_comp increases monotonically with the total proto-brick count of the topological knot: light knots with few proto-bricks have low E_comp and are easily breached by external compression energy; heavy knots with many proto-bricks have very high E_comp and can withstand stronger compression without disintegration. This systematic difference is the cornerstone of nuclear transition channel selection and astrophysical evolution paths.

Part IV: Nuclear Transitions—Four Reaction Channels

Interactions between topological knots are essentially the complementary matching of surface topological defects and the reconfiguration of binding edges. When any two topological knots a and b meet, depending on conditions, they can enter one of the following four channels.

Channel I: Defect-Complementary Weaving (Path I)

Condition: The topological defects on the surfaces of the two topological knots are exactly geometrically complementary.

Process: The defect regions of the two knots interlock; binding edges reconfigure, fusing the two knots into a single larger topological knot x. The stress change released (i.e., energy) equals the total inertia deficit of the participating topological knots.

Characteristics:
The sole threshold for Path I is the geometric matching of defects, independent of any energy barrier. The "Coulomb barrier" in the Standard Model is reinterpreted in this framework as an apparent form of the Path II trigger threshold E_comp under charged conditions—the Coulomb barrier is a macroscopic projection of E_comp, not the threshold for Path I. Temperature serves to increase collision frequency and thermal vibration amplitude, thereby raising the probability of defect exposure and matching.

The polymerization pathway (stepwise or "checker-jumping") is dynamically determined by the raw material abundance ratio: when a certain light nucleus is overwhelmingly dominant, stepwise polymerization is the dominant channel; when multiple nuclide abundances are comparable, checker-jumping cross-mass polymerization becomes significant. The deeper meaning of the checker-jumping path is that multiple precursor combinations can converge to the same final state; the abundance of a nuclide is the sum of the contributions of all channels in the fully connected reaction network that can reach that node.

Path I possesses a negative-feedback self-stabilization loop in fluid media: local heat release → expansion → density decrease → increased defect spacing → decreased matching probability → heat release automatically reduced. In solid media, due to lack of rapid heat dissipation and immediate expansion response, this negative feedback cannot be established, potentially leading to continuous energy accumulation.

Definition of Channel I Probability:
The probability of Path I polymerization in a single collision depends on three factors:

Intrinsic defect area ratio of the nuclide: heavy nuclei are densely woven, have small defect area ratios, correspondingly lower matching probability.
Ambient compressive intensity: high pressure stretches the weaving network, exposing more effective defect area, increasing matching probability.
Defect complementary matching efficiency: jointly determined by the topological type and geometric shape of the defects on both sides.
The macroscopic reaction rate is proportional to the product of single-collision polymerization probability and particle number density. When the total number of particles is extremely large, even if the single-event probability is extremely low, the absolute number of events can still reach macroscopically observable levels—an inevitable consequence of the law of large numbers, and the statistical basis for energy release inside stars and planets.

Channel II: Forced Chain Reconnection (Path II)

Condition: External compression energy (from any form of extreme pressurization such as gravity, shock waves, laser fusion, etc.) exceeds the total compressive binding energy E_comp of the topological knot.

Process: Binding edges are severed in batches; the core weaving network is exposed, undergoing large-scale forced chain reconnection. In a single event, numerous topological knots are simultaneously dismantled and reconstructed in an extremely short time. E_comp is both the threshold for the nuclide's own resistance to compression and the trigger condition for Path II—they are the potential-energy and event descriptions of the same thing.

Characteristics:
Path II does not depend on defect matching probability; once triggered, it proceeds inevitably and cannot be regulated by environmental feedback. Its trigger condition is universal: the source of external compression energy is not limited to gravity—any form of extreme pressurization/heating, such as laser fusion, magnetic confinement, shock waves, etc., as long as the injected energy exceeds the nuclide's E_comp, can forcibly trigger Path II.

The trigger threshold E_comp increases with the total proto-brick count of the nuclide, which constitutes a form of passive self-stabilization: when the core region consists mainly of heavy nuclei, even if stress accumulates, Path II is difficult to trigger.
E_comp is a single unified threshold for a nuclide's resistance to external compression—the observational effects described by "Coulomb barrier" and "degeneracy pressure" in the Standard Model correspond respectively to different apparent forms of E_comp under charged conditions and extreme density conditions in this framework, both originating from the same source.

The energy released by Path II manifests as a shock wave; wave speeds in solid-state topological networks can reach on the order of 0.3c to c. The energy released by Path II is far less than the total internal energy of the star; after the event, the star returns to Path I state to re-accumulate stress.

Channel III: Topological Dissolution (Path III)

Condition: The algebraic sum of the global topological charges of two topological knots a and b is exactly zero.

Process: Defect-complementary interlocking does not form new stable weaves; instead, due to global stress returning to zero, complete deconstruction occurs—all binding edges are simultaneously removed, and all topological nodes return to the zero-topological-charge planar membrane ground state. The final state is pure radiation; 100% of the mass is converted into energy.

Characteristics:
Path III shares the trigger condition of "defect-complementary interlocking" with Path I, but the interlocking outcome is entirely different. The probability of Path III is exceedingly rare under natural conditions. Crucial point: Path III only blocks specific reaction channels (a+b → pure radiation); it does not mean that nuclides of that mass number cannot be synthesized via other precursor combinations (a'+b'). Therefore, the "absolute forbidden zones" caused by Path III exist at the level of reaction channels, not at the level of nuclides.

Channel IV: Stress Tearing (Fission)

Condition: The stress accumulated on a certain suture line inside an existing topological knot x exceeds the instantaneous bearing limit of the binding edges.

Process: The configuration undergoes mechanical tearing along that suture line, splitting into two smaller nuclei c and d. The energy released equals the reduction in total inertia before and after tearing.

Characteristics:
Fission probability depends on the stress distribution along the internal suture lines of the nuclide and is an intrinsic property of the nuclide, independent of its synthesis pathway. Nuclides with excessively high fission probability have extremely short half-lives and very low abundances.

Part V: Element Abundances and the Iron Peak—Three-Factor Criterion

5.1 The Three-Factor Criterion

In the reaction network constituted by the four channels, the cosmic abundance of any nuclide is jointly determined by the following three probabilities:

Synthesis probability: the probability that the nuclide is produced through various precursor channels (stepwise, checker-jumping, products of Path I or Path II subsequently cooled). If a channel is blocked by Path III, that contribution is zero, but the nuclide can still be synthesized via other channels.
Continued fusion probability: the probability that the nuclide, acting as a reactant, continues to polymerize into heavier nuclides via Path I or Path II.
Fission probability: the probability that the nuclide fissions back into lighter nuclei due to internal stress tearing.
These three jointly determine the net retention of a nuclide on the mass spectrum:
Net retention ∝ Synthesis probability × (1 − Continued fusion probability − Fission probability)

Abundance peaks occur at nuclides where synthesis probability is appreciable, but both continued fusion probability and fission probability are low—nucleon flux can arrive, but once there, it neither easily moves forward nor is easily pushed back, resulting in net accumulation.
Abundance valleys occur at nuclides where synthesis probability is low, or continued fusion probability is high, or fission probability is high—nucleon flux either cannot arrive, or cannot stay if it does.
The entire elemental abundance distribution of the periodic table is the comprehensive projection of these three probabilities continuously varying across the mass spectrum. Path III only excludes specific reaction channels and does not affect the synthesis probability of that nuclide via other channels.

5.2 Checker-Jumping Paths and Stepwise Paths

In this framework, there is no "mandatory path" on the nuclide mass spectrum. Any two topological knots (whether light, medium, or heavy) can polymerize as long as their defects match. Reaction probability depends on the geometric compatibility of the defects on both sides, with no rigid constraint based on their positions on the mass spectrum.

Checker-jumping paths and stepwise paths are not mutually exclusive; they are two parallel channels whose weights are determined by raw material abundance ratios.

The deeper meaning of checker-jumping: multiple precursor combinations can converge to the same final state. For example, a topological knot of mass number 36 can be synthesized via magnesium + carbon (24+12), oxygen + neon (16+20), and other checker-jumping paths. Mass number 40 can be synthesized via silicon + carbon (28+12), magnesium + oxygen (24+16), etc. The abundance of a nuclide is not the output of a fixed assembly line, but the sum of contributions from all channels in the fully connected reaction network that can converge to that node. This is "checker-jumping"—nucleon flux does not travel along a single line, but jumps across mass numbers and converges through multiple paths. Path III only blocks specific channels and does not prevent other channels from continuing to supply that nuclide.

5.3 The Iron Peak: Concrete Manifestation of the Three-Factor Criterion

The prominent abundance of Iron-56 is a concrete realization of the above three-factor criterion at mass number 56, not originating from any special mechanism:

Synthesis probability: Nucleon flux can reach mass number 56 through both stepwise paths and checker-jumping paths. The weighted sum of the two pathways, dynamically regulated by precursor abundance ratios, keeps synthesis probability appreciable at A=56.
Continued fusion probability: The defect area ratio of the topological knot at mass number 56 is extremely small, so the probability of continuing to polymerize upward as a reactant is low. Nucleon flux "moves forward" slowly here.
Fission probability: The internal suture line stresses of the topological knot at mass number 56 are balanced, so the probability of being torn back into lighter nuclei is also low. Nucleon flux "is pushed back" slowly here.
The superposition of these three: nucleon flux can reach mass number 56, but once there, the rates of moving forward and flowing backward are both low—net accumulation. This is the entire cause of the iron peak. Checker-jumping paths contribute additional channels when precursor abundances are suitable, but the position and magnitude of the iron abundance peak are ultimately still determined by the three-factor criterion. Path choice only affects the numerical value of the "synthesis probability" term, without altering the structure of the three-factor framework.
5.4 Astrophysical Role of Iron Cores

The iron peak has no causal relationship with stellar evolution. The prominence of iron in abundance is merely a large net accumulation of nucleon flux at that point; it does not determine any evolutionary turning point of the star.

The special role of an iron core in stellar evolution arises from its extremely high total compressive binding energy E_comp. In the Standard Model, the formation of an iron core signifies that nuclear fusion no longer releases heat, forcing core collapse. In this framework, the role of the iron core is completely different:

The Path I polymerization probability of an iron core is extremely low (defect area ratio extremely small); the heat release from Path I is almost frozen.
However, the iron core's E_comp is extremely high, so the iron core can withstand enormous gravitational compression energy without triggering Path II.
The essence of an iron core is a "rigid core supported by total compressive binding energy, with nuclear reactions nearly frozen."
When peripheral matter continues to accumulate, and the gravitational compression energy exceeds the E_comp threshold of the iron core, Path II is triggered. The mass corresponding to this threshold is observationally approximately 1.4 M_⊙, explaining the explosion characteristics of iron-core supernovae around that mass. The Standard Model attributes this value to the electron degeneracy pressure limit (Chandrasekhar limit); this framework reinterprets it as the threshold at which the iron core's E_comp is breached.
Part VI: Interactions—Geometry of Shared Links

Postulate 9: Shared Links

The multiple connection pathways established between two topological knots through intermediate loops on the membrane are called shared links. Shared links are the sole medium of interaction between topological knots.

No independent "force" entities exist. All interactions are manifestations of the geometric properties of shared links.

The five geometric parameters of shared links also govern the microscopic process of Path I defect matching—link density gradients can influence defect exposure probability, link orientation can influence defect alignment, etc. All nuclear transition channels can find corresponding descriptions within the geometric framework of shared links.

Definition 9.1: Five Geometric Parameters of Shared Links

All interactions can be reduced to the following five geometric parameters of shared links:

Parameter	Definition	Macroscopic Manifestation
Total Number of Links	Number of independent connection paths between two topological knots	Gravitational Strength
Link Orientation Degree	Statistical uniformity of shared link spatial directions	Magnetic Strength
Link Density Gradient	Rate of change of link count in space	Electric Strength
Link Saturation	Proportion of connected paths among all possible connection pathways	Strong Nuclear Force (attraction/repulsion)
Link Fragility	Probability of disconnection under perturbation	Weak Force Decay Rate
6.1 Construction of a Discrete Gauge Field

Definition 9.2 (Combinatorial Covariant Derivative): Let the discrete phase field of shared links be Θ(r_i), defined on lattice nodes i. Let A_ij be the orientation tensor contribution of background shared links between nodes i and j. Define the combinatorial covariant derivative:
D_ij Θ ≡ Θ(r_j) − Θ(r_i) − A_ij
where:
Θ(r_i) ∈ Z is the phase of the shared link at node i (count of reconnection steps).
A_ij is the background orientation field generated between nodes i, j due to periodic arrangement of atomic nuclei, defined as the minimum number of reconnection steps along the i→j direction.
All quantities are purely discrete, independent of any continuous spatial metric.

6.2 Geometric Definition of the Superconducting State

Definition 9.3 (Superconducting State): If and only if for all nearest-neighbor node pairs ⟨i, j⟩, the covariant derivative vanishes:
D_ij Θ = 0, ∀⟨i,j⟩ ∈ conducting network
the system is in global phase locking—all shared links perform helical motion in perfect synchrony.

6.3 Discrete Derivation of the First London Equation

The macroscopic current density J is defined in TDMU as the directed shared link flux. When the system deviates from the perfect superconducting state but still maintains phase coherence, there exists a residual value of the covariant derivative. This residual drives the directed link flux:
J ∝ Σ_⟨i,j⟩ D_ij Θ
In the continuum limit, D_ij Θ corresponds to the covariant derivative ∇Θ − A, hence:
J = −(1/Λ) A
where Λ is the geometric inertia constant of the shared link network, determined by the total number of links per unit volume N_total: Λ ∝ 1/N_total. This is the purely discrete form of the first London equation.

6.4 Geometric Necessity of the Meissner Effect

Taking the discrete curl (summing along the smallest closed path) of the London equation:
∇ × J = −(1/Λ) (∇ × A) = −(1/Λ) B
Inside the superconducting state, all D_ij Θ = 0, so the spatial distribution of J is completely determined by the configuration of A_ij, and ∇ × J = 0.
From this it follows that B = 0 strictly holds inside the superconductor.

The penetration depth λ_L = √Λ is defined as the geometric yielding step count of the shared link network—i.e., the characteristic length over which an external orientation gradient (magnetic field), upon entering the synchronized link network, is completely screened after λ_L steps of reconnection propagation.

6.5 Topological Necessity of Flux Quantization

Consider a closed path C on a superconducting ring. The phase Θ must return to the same discrete count after one full loop, so the total phase change is an integer multiple of 2π (Θ is the number of helical steps modulo 2π).

Summing the covariant derivative along the closed path:
∮_C DΘ · dl = 2π n, n ∈ Z
In the superconducting state, DΘ = 0 holds inside the ring body, but along a closed path enclosing the hole, the contribution of A is not canceled. Thus:
∮_C DΘ · dl = ∮_C A · dl = Φ
Combining:
Φ = n · Φ₀, Φ₀ = 2π

Magnetic flux is rigorously quantized in TDMU geometric natural units as integer multiples of the fundamental unit Φ₀ = 2π.

Note 9.1 (Unit Mapping and Falsification Condition): The precise mapping relationship between Φ₀ = 2π in TDMU geometric natural units and the experimentally measured flux quantum Φ₀,exp = h/2e requires establishing correspondence rules for "reconnection step number—action" and "total links—charge." This is a core task of TDMU metrology and will be completed as an independent supplement.

Nevertheless, TDMU has independently proven the existence and structure of flux quantization—namely, that magnetic flux must be an integer multiple of an irreducible fundamental unit, the existence of which arises from the topological necessity of closed paths, not from any dynamical assumption.

Note 9.2 (Preliminary Bridging Path for Λ to Experimentally Measurable Parameters):
The geometric inertia constant Λ is defined as the purely geometric quantity satisfying the London equation J = −(1/Λ)A, with Λ ∝ 1/N_total (N_total being the total number of shared links participating in conduction per unit volume). This definition is rigorous at the combinatorial network level, but N_total cannot be directly extracted from experimental readings.

To render the prediction for superconducting penetration depth preliminarily testable, we propose a bridging hypothesis (H0) connecting Λ to conventional condensed matter parameters:
In metal-superconductor systems, the total number of shared links per unit volume N_total is proportional to the density of effective dangling link ports in a unit cell. Let n_port be the number of dangling link ports participating in the conduction band per formula unit, and V_cell the cell volume. Then:
N_total ∝ n_port / V_cell
Based on this, the predicted penetration depth λ_L should satisfy:
λ_L ∝ √(V_cell / n_port)
That is, for superconductors of the same family, λ_L² · (n_port / V_cell) should be approximately constant.

Honest Note: The above H0 is the first mapping hypothesis between TDMU geometric language and experimental measurements. If supported by preliminary experimental data, it will provide a key anchor for the subsequent establishment of a complete mapping from "reconnection steps—action" to SI units; if negated, the definition of N_total will need revision. The testing of this hypothesis itself is one of the core tasks of TDMU metrology and does not affect the validity of the core geometric conclusion that "the structure of flux quantization originates from closed path topology."

6.6 Geometric Definitions of the Five Forces

Definition 9.4: Gravity
The larger the total number of shared links between two topological knots, the stronger the membrane's tendency to reduce overall stress—this tendency macroscopically manifests as pulling the two knots toward each other.
Gravity is a large-number statistical effect of total shared links. No graviton is required.

Definition 9.5: Magnetism
When shared links exhibit statistically non-uniform distribution in spatial directions, a macroscopic torsional stress field is generated. The streamlines of this stress field are magnetic field lines.
The closed nature of magnetic field lines is a topological necessity—shared links cannot have isolated endpoints in space.
Magnetic monopoles are topologically forbidden.

Definition 9.6: Electricity
Density gradients of shared links generate normal stress waves. A stress difference exists between regions of excess density and regions of deficit density.
Excess–excess (or deficit–deficit) → repulsive stress difference.
Excess–deficit → attractive stress difference.
Electricity is the orthogonal deformation mode of magnetism—the two together constitute the complete linear response of shared link perturbations.

Definition 9.7: Strong Nuclear Force
When the distance between two topological knots shrinks such that the saturation of shared links approaches its maximum:
Shared links form an indivisible shared network → disassembly requires simultaneous severing of a large number of links → attraction.
If the distance shrinks further, shared link paths are forced to bend → generating repulsive bow-like stress → repulsion.
The strong nuclear force is the nonlinear behavioral mode of shared links at extremely short distances.

Definition 9.8: Weak Interaction
When the distance between two topological knots lies in the critical range where shared links are "just barely establishable," the number of shared links is extremely small. This few-link state is metastable—any local reconnection perturbation can cause link breakage and trigger cascade disintegration.
The weak interaction is not a "force," but the spontaneous decay mode of a metastable shared-link network.

Definition 9.9: Electric Current
In a conductor, the shared links of topological knots on the atomic nucleus surfaces are distributed along closed paths in the absence of external fields—this is the lowest-energy mode of shared links in cylindrical geometry.
An external field (density gradient of shared links) stretches these closed paths into helical paths along the conductor direction. The helically advancing shared links drag the peripheral electron-bricks into synchronous motion.
Electric current is the collective manifestation of helical shared-link motion. Electrical resistance is the frequency statistic of collisions and reconnections of shared links in motion.

Definition 9.10: Superconductivity
When the helical motion of shared links achieves complete synchronization—all links are in phase, collision frequency drops to zero—the shared links enter a dissipationless transmission state.
Superconductivity is the synchronization phase transition of the collective motion mode of shared links.

Part VII: Complete Life Cycle of the Universe and the Genealogy of Astrophysical Evolution

Postulate 10: Origin

In a region of the substrate, loop density exceeds the critical value due to random fluctuation. Large numbers of positive and negative direction loops form pairing structures, squeezed and contracted by peripheral circulating flows beyond their elastic recovery point. At the critical point, the system destabilizes; topological elastic potential energy drives the loop surface to evert and roll outward, forming a closed membrane.
The Big Bang is the elastic release of the membrane from a super-coiled state.

Honest Note: "Random fluctuation" is currently the simplest description of the initial condition. The model cannot explain why it was this region, at this moment, a single membrane rather than multiple. These are incompletenesses on the same level as the singularity problem in standard cosmology.

Postulate 11: Evolution

After formation, the membrane continuously expands. Expansion causes an overall decrease in loop density on the membrane—i.e., cosmic cooling. Temperature is the local manifestation of loop density gradients.

During cooling, topological knots emerge sequentially: proto-bricks → electron-bricks → leptons → mesons → baryons → atomic nuclei → atoms → molecules.
Each step is the most stable woven structure "allowed to exist" at the current loop density.

The current universe is in an intermediate state where "loop density is sufficiently low, but not yet low enough for membrane dissolution."

Postulate 12: Finale

The membrane is always a part of the substrate. The circulating flow pressure from the region outside the membrane does not decay with the membrane's expansion. When the loop density on the membrane falls below a critical value, the compressive strength of the membrane will become lower than the external circulating flow pressure, and the membrane will enter irreversible structural instability.

Final outcome: Global topological reconnection dissolution—the membrane fragments into discrete loops and returns to the substrate.
The universe ends as a coherent topological entity.

Honest Note: The specific numerical value of the critical density, the dynamical path of instability, and the time scale of the finale—none of these can be derived from the model. The model can only qualitatively predict "the existence of an irreversible critical point."

7.1 The Continuous Spectrum of Celestial Bodies: From Solid Planets to Stars

In TDMU 2.32, astrophysical evolution is refined as the dynamic game among Path I, Path II, Fission, and Path III at different scales. Celestial body composition forms a complete continuous spectrum from solid planets to quasars. All celestial bodies, in macroscopic observation, follow a single fundamental law: reduction of total mass converted into energy release. Path I, Path II, and their mixed states are merely different mechanisms for realizing this mass-energy conversion, not two different physical essences.

7.1.1 Solid Planets: The Death Line and Survival Conditions

Solid media have two fatal weaknesses: extremely slow heat dissipation (heat conducted by lattice vibrations, far less efficient than fluid convection), and severely restricted thermal expansion (constrained by the crystal lattice, local temperature rises do not immediately cause density decreases).

Once the Path I reaction rate in the core of a solid planet enters positive feedback—higher temperature accelerates reactions, faster reactions raise temperature further—the solid medium can neither dissipate heat fast enough nor expand to lower the reaction rate. Local temperature skyrockets exponentially, breaching the binding edge batch-breaking threshold in an extremely short time. Path II is detonated, and the entire planet is dismantled layer by layer from the core outward.

This is why the observed exoplanet radius distribution features a "planetary radius gap"—many small solid planets exist, many large gaseous planets exist, but large solid planets are almost absent. Not that they didn't form, but that they formed and then exploded.

Critical condition: Solid planets have a critical mass upper limit. For planets exceeding this mass, regardless of their initial temperature, the core Path I thermal runaway velocity will exceed the lattice heat conduction velocity, triggering irreversible positive feedback until Path II detonation. The exact value of this critical mass depends on the geometric parameters of topological defects, but the existence of a critical mass is a deterministic prediction of the model.

Survival condition: If a solid planet's mass is below the critical value, or internal radioactive decay/tidal heating is sufficient to heat the core to melting temperature, the medium acquires fluid properties—convective heat dissipation and thermal expansion response begin to function. Path I's negative feedback mechanism can be established, and the star may stably exist.

7.1.2 Gaseous Planets: Smoldering Topological Furnaces

Fluid media dissipate heat quickly, expand when heated, and density decreases, automatically down-regulating the reaction rate. From mini-Neptunes to hot Jupiters to brown dwarfs, gaseous planets stably exist over a wide mass range.

Anomalous heat flow of Jupiter and Saturn: Juno measured Jupiter's net internal heat flow at about 5.5×10¹⁷ W; Cassini measured Saturn's internal heat flow at 2.84±0.20 W/m² and discovered a 16.0±4.2% seasonal dynamic imbalance in its energy budget. The Standard Model explains this with "gravitational contraction," but its timescale is only ~10⁷ years, far shorter than the solar system's age, and seasonal fluctuations directly contradict the monotonically decreasing expectation of gravitational contraction.

Path I unified explanation: The cores of both Jupiter and Saturn operate Path I defect-complementary weaving reactions, differing only in macroscopic event rates. The interlocking event rate for both is about 10⁹ times lower than that of the Sun. The released energy is entirely bound internally by gravity—the gravitational potential well depth is sufficient to convert all radiation products into heat and turbulence, incapable of producing ionizing radiation. The macroscopic manifestation is "excess heat" rather than luminescence.

7.1.3 The Topological Furnace Spectrum

The Sun, Jupiter, and Saturn form a complete spectrum from "burning" to "smoldering." Planets are not "failed stars." They are topological furnaces where gravity has compressed the nuclear fire to just a smolder, rather than fully extinguishing it.

7.1.4 Stars: Main-Sequence Equilibrium and Checker-Jumping Burning

When the mass of a gaseous clump exceeds a critical threshold, the core's defect matching probability breaks through a key threshold—the defect-complementary matching probability between hydrogen topological knots rises high enough to support the luminosity of the entire clump.

Essence of the main sequence: Under conditions of rapid heat dissipation and instantaneous thermal expansion feedback provided by the fluid medium, the Path I defect matching probability and the environmental thermodynamic response reach dynamic equilibrium. Core temperature rises → defects exposed more fully → matching probability increases → heat release increases → core expands → density decreases → defect spacing increases → matching probability decreases → heat release decreases → core contracts → density increases → matching probability rises. This negative feedback loop allows the star to burn stably on the main sequence for billions of years.

Checker-Jumping Nuclear Burning: Nucleon flux in a stellar core is not a one-way street. Checker-jumping paths allow polymerization between any two nuclides. Light-nucleus fusion dominates the luminosity, while medium and heavy-nucleus fusion runs in parallel at lower rates. The stellar core is effectively a fully connected reaction pool—different reaction channels operate in parallel under the same temperature-density conditions, with rates determined individually by the three factors. Path choice is dynamically determined by precursor abundance ratios.

Multi-nuclide Synergistic Support: The pressure balance in a stellar core is not provided solely by the currently dominant nuclide. Different nuclides like hydrogen, helium, carbon, and oxygen each contribute Path I thermal pressure, while heavy nuclei (iron group) provide structural strength buffering due to their high Path II trigger threshold E_comp. The actual timescale of stellar evolution is the result of multi-nuclide synergistic support.

7.2 Stellar Dynamic Cycle: Two Contests, Regenerative Ignition, and Recycling

The fate of a star is determined by two contests:

First Contest: External compression energy input rate vs. Path I reaction release rate.
In stars, the source of external compression energy is work done by gravitational compression.
The release rate of Path I depends on the polymerization probability of the currently dominant core nuclide.
If Path I release rate ≥ external compression input rate → stable burning.
If external compression input rate > Path I release rate → net accumulation of internal stress in nuclides.

Second Contest: Accumulated external compression energy vs. nuclide total compressive binding energy E_comp.
Contraction causes density and temperature to rise; binding edge stress continuously increases.
When accumulated compression energy exceeds E_comp → Path II is triggered.
If Path II energy release > gravitational binding energy → explosion.
If Path II energy release < gravitational binding energy → silent collapse.

This criterion is universal: gravitational compression (stellar cores, planetary interiors), laser/particle beam impact (inertial confinement fusion), magnetic confinement compression (tokamaks), shock wave compression (supernova shocks)—any form of extreme pressurization/heating, as long as the energy injection exceeds E_comp, triggers Path II.

7.3 Regenerative Ignition: Topological Reset Bypassing the Fusion Trap

In the Standard Model, stellar evolution is a unidirectional irreversible process: H → He → C → O → Si → Fe → collapse/explosion. In this framework, evolution is redefined as a dynamic cycle between Path I and Path II:

Normal burning phase (Path I): Polymerization into heavier nuclides via checker-jumping paths, releasing energy.
Encountering a "fusion trap" phase: When core nuclides reach a certain mass number (e.g., near A=56), the polymerization probability of Path I plummets due to the extremely small defect area ratio. The Standard Model posits that the star must then collapse or explode.
Path II assisted disassembly (Topological Reset): Gravitational compression leads to stress accumulation; accumulated compression energy exceeds the E_comp of that nuclide, locally triggering Path II (forced reconnection), forcibly disassembling the accumulated heavy nuclei into lighter nuclides (e.g., splitting A=56 into A=28+28, or lighter fragments).
Regenerative Ignition: The light nuclear fragments produced by disassembly re-enter the Path I reactant pool and undergo reactions with higher defect matching probability with the remaining fuel, releasing energy anew. The star "bypasses" the fusion trap, re-entering the energy release cycle under the macroscopic principle of overall mass reduction converted to energy release.
Correspondence with observations:

Certain white dwarfs may be in a quiescent period of "Path I frozen, awaiting topological reset followed by regenerative ignition."
Nova/dwarf nova outbursts (especially recurrent cataclysmic variables) could be cyclic processes of Path II local disassembly → Path I re-ignition.
The central sources in some supernova remnants may be residual cores after a Path II outburst, where peripheral remnant material is compressed by the shock wave and re-ignited.
Core Principle: There is no true "finale," only "switching between Path I and Path II." The star only follows the single fundamental macroscopic observational phenomenon of overall mass reduction converted into energy release.

7.4 Mixed-State Stars: Symbiosis of Path I and Path II

Stars are not simply divided into "Path I dominated" or "Path II dominated," but exist on a continuous spectrum:

Star Type	Path I Fraction	Path II Fraction	Macroscopic Manifestation	Typical Representatives
Pure Path I Star	~100%	~0%	Stable luminosity	Main-sequence stars
Path I Dominant	>90%	<10%	Stable burning, occasional flares	Red giant cores, AGB stars
Mixed State	50%-90%	10%-50%	Periodic brightness fluctuations	Cepheids, Mira variables
Path II Dominant	<50%	>50%	Structural reorganization after violent outburst	Residual cores of some supernova remnants
Pure Path II Star	~0%	~100%	Extreme luminosity, internal storms	Quasars (early)
Key Inference: Mixed-state stars are not necessarily "transitional phases in evolution" but could be steady-state structures—Path I burning gently in the core periphery, Path II periodically triggering and self-restoring at internal stress hotspots, forming a pulsation equilibrium. This explains the periodic light variations of Cepheids: internal Path II local triggering (stress release), structural re-stabilization, Path I taking over again, then stress re-accumulation, repeating cyclically.

7.5 Dense Topological Stars: The Compression Limit State

When the energy released by Path II is insufficient to completely blow apart the star, the remnant is compressed to the extreme by gravity. In this extreme compression state, topological knot spheres are compressed to the limit, surface structures collapse—the defect area ratio approaches 100%, and the entire star is in a "fully surface-reconnectable" state.

Definition of Dense Topological Star: A dense aggregate of topological knots compressed to a defect fraction approaching 100%, where the distinction of "stable nuclides" no longer exists. In the compression limit state, the surface weaving of topological knots has been completely destroyed; all nodes are in a connection-saturated state—every edge in the network has reached its maximum coordination number and cannot accept new connections. At this point, any further compression requires the network to add new connections, which is prohibited under local reconnection rules. This is the support mechanism of the compression limit state: the connection saturation rigidity of the network—the topological counterpart of "degeneracy pressure" in the Standard Model within TDMU.

7.6 Quasars: Imprisoned Ultimate Weaving Storms

Quasars are the brightest objects in the universe, with typical luminosities reaching 10⁴⁰–10⁴¹ W, and variability timescales as short as days, indicating that the energy release region is no larger than the solar system. They exist in the very early universe (z > 6). The Standard Model interprets them as supermassive black hole accretion disks, but faces a time dilemma: how could supermassive black holes of ~10⁹ M_⊙ form within just a few hundred million years of cosmic birth?

This model's answer: Reconnection storms imprisoned by the convergence effect. In the very early universe, for sufficiently massive primordial topological knot clumps, the core Path II chain-reconnection wave is blocked from penetrating the clump boundary by the convergence effect of the vast peripheral shared links, forming a sustained internal circulation reconnection storm. Fission cycles and Path III superimpose to contribute extreme luminosity. Quasars are not formed by stellar collapse but skip the stellar stage, directly entering an imprisoned reconnection storm from primordial gas clumps. This circumvents the time dilemma of the Standard Model.

Part VIII: Testable Directions

8.1 Spatial Variation of the Gravitational Constant
Gravity is a statistical effect of the total number of shared links. Prediction: The effective gravitational constant in dense environments should be higher than the solar system value.

8.2 Local-Global Discrepancy of the Hubble Constant
Prediction: Locally measured values should be systematically higher than CMB-inferred values, with the difference proportional to local loop density fluctuations.

8.3 Non-constancy of the Dark Energy Equation of State
Prediction: w(z) ≠ −1 and evolves with time.

8.4 Chiral Polarization Residuals
Prediction: Primordial gravitational waves or the CMB may contain a weak circular polarization component.

8.5 Magnetism in Non-metals under Extreme Conditions
Prediction: Under high pressure/low temperature/doping, non-metals could exhibit statistical magnetic effects.

8.6 Periodic Structure of the Superconducting Surface Magnetic Field
Prediction: In the superconducting state, the surface magnetic field distribution exhibits periodic modulation related to the lattice constant.

8.7 Inflection of the Cosmic Expansion Deceleration Parameter
Prediction: q(z) exhibits a transition from negative to positive at some redshift.

8.8 Solid Planet Mass Upper Limit
Solid planets exceeding a certain critical mass cannot exist stably. If a large number of long-term stable purely solid planets are found across an arbitrary mass range (with no cutoff signature), this framework is falsified.

8.9 Compact Object Disassembly Window
In a certain mass interval between dense topological stars and topological stars, Path II is reactivated, and any compact object will be completely blown apart. If a complete continuous mass distribution is found between dense topological stars and supermassive compact objects, this framework is falsified.

8.10 Non-Accretion-Disk Nature of Quasars
If quasar energy spectra and variability characteristics are rigorously proven to be completely consistent with the accretion disk model, and EHT imaging confirms event horizon features at quasar centers, this framework requires revision.

8.11 Regenerative Ignition Phenomena
Signals of re-ignited nuclear burning exist at the centers of some supernova remnants; some white dwarf nova outbursts after mass accretion exhibit repeatable multi-cycle outburst patterns. If all observed stellar evolution strictly conforms to a unidirectional irreversible sequence, this framework requires revision.

8.12 Pulsation Equilibrium of Mixed-State Stars
The period-luminosity relationship of pulsating variables should have a precise correspondence with the radial distribution of E_comp inside the star. If it can be fully explained by pure fluid dynamics mechanisms, the mixed-state interpretation of this framework is challenged.

8.13 Laboratory Test of Exchange Parity and Pauli Exclusion
Prediction: In any stable atom, electron-bricks must occupy mutually distinct spatial winding modes; shell filling numbers are strictly 2n². If a stable configuration is found in a stable atom where two electron-bricks occupy exactly the same spatial winding mode with zero phase difference—i.e., Pauli exclusion is systematically violated—this framework is falsified.

8.14 Discrete Jumps in Isotope Fission Thresholds
Prediction: In isotope chains, the variation of the fission cross-section with neutron number should exhibit discrete jumps related to the vacancy pattern of the 12³ closure, rather than strict monotonic variation. If fission thresholds are observed to vary strictly monotonically with neutron number without any discrete jumps related to closure matching, this framework requires revision.

8.15 Topological Test of Flux Quantization Structure
Prediction: Magnetic flux must be an integer multiple of an irreducible fundamental unit; the penetration depth λ_L should satisfy λ_L ∝ √(V_cell / n_port) with respect to the density of dangling link ports in the unit cell. If magnetic flux is observed in any superconducting system not to be an integer multiple of an irreducible fundamental unit, this framework is falsified.

8.16 Cross-Scale Test of the Hierarchical Cutoff Criterion
Prediction: From subatomic to cosmic scales, the effective counting range of shared links should follow the cutoff rule of Corollary 3.1—i.e., decay exponentially to zero when d_AB > κ · (r_A + r_B). If at any scale the interaction strength of shared links is found to exhibit sustained linear growth independent of the cutoff radius, this framework requires revision.

Part IX: Unfinished Problems and Honest Boundaries

The following problems remain unclosed in the current TDMU 2.32 state:

The analytical value of the critical loop density for the membrane.
The general mapping function from topological charge to observed mass (including specific numerical relationships of the recursive growth tree).
The precise dynamical rules of recursive growth—complete classification of defect compatibility.
Rigorous logical proof of reconnection irreversibility (currently a statistical assumption).
The precise location and time of the universe's final critical point.
The emergence conditions for three spatial dimensions.
Quantitative correspondence between the five geometric parameters of shared links and known physical laws (inverse square law, Maxwell's equations, Yukawa potential, Fermi coupling constant).
The first-principles calculation method for E_comp and its functional relationship with nuclide mass number (Note: the precise numerical calculation of I has been explicitly identified as an independent task).
Rigorous elevation of the geometric simulation of Path I polymerization probability to discrete network statistical mechanics.
The exact suppression factor of Path III and its impact on early-universe element abundances.
Analytical expression for the stability threshold of the "rigid core + soft outer layer" binary structure in the recursive growth tree.
The energy scale at which the outer layer structure of the electron-brick can be excited, and its observable signatures.
Complete derivation of shell filling numbers 2n²—from the discrete combinatorial rules of port winding to a discretized version of spherical harmonics.
The complete mapping system from TDMU geometric units (Φ₀ = 2π, reconnection step count, etc.) to SI units.
The precise range of κ in the hierarchical cutoff criterion and its functional relationship with local loop density.
Conclusion

The entire content of physics—space, time, matter, gravity, magnetism, electricity, nuclear force, weak force, electric current, superconductivity, nuclear transitions, elemental abundances, astrophysical evolution, the origin and finale of the universe, the geometric enforcement of quantum statistics, the geometric decoupling of isotope fission, the topological origin of superconducting gauge fields—all reduce to three things:
Nodes, Directed Edges, Shared Links.

Plus two emergent principles:
Recursive Weaving and Defect Complementarity.

And one hierarchical cutoff criterion:
The geometric window of effective interaction is determined by the recursive growth radius.

This is the first-principles formulation of TDMU 2.32. It does not rely on any pre-set physical quantities, does not invoke any concepts that cannot be translated back to nodes and edges, and does not evade any unsolved problems. There are no absolute "elementary particles," only eternal recursion and emergence. There is no true "finale," only dynamic switching between Path I and Path II.

The toad still rests quietly in the unreachable depths of the substrate. But the wall of the bubble it blew has now been precisely translated by us into discrete weaving between nodes and edges, the parity of reconnection steps, the stress concentration of the hierarchical compressive tensor, the covariant derivative of the discrete phase field—and a clear geometric cutoff: fibers exceeding the sum of recursive growth radii no longer belong to this bubble.

This is the complete picture of the Topological Dynamical Membrane Universe—V2.32.

